1) What is constructor in java? What is the use of constructors?
-->A constructor in Java is a special block of code that is automatically called when an instance (object) of a class is created. It has the
    same name as the class and does not have an explicit return type—not even void
    👉 A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects
    
    Same name as class
    No return type
    
    ✔ Use:
    
    Initialize variables
    Allocate resources
    Set default values


2) What are the different types of constructors?
-->Default constructor (no parameters)
    Parameterized constructor
    Copy constructor (user-defined)

    Default Constructor: If a developer does not define any constructor, the Java compiler automatically inserts a default no-args constructor, setting 
    fields to default values (e.g., , null, false).
    No-Argument Constructor (User-Defined): A constructor explicitly written by the developer that takes no parameters. It is used to provide
    custom initialization values.
    Parameterized Constructor: A constructor that accepts one or more arguments, allowing the creation of objects with specific, custom values.
    Constructor Overloading: A class can have multiple constructors, provided their parameter lists differ (different number or types of arguments).
    Copy Constructor (Concept): Although Java does not have a built-in copy constructor like C++, you can create a parameterized constructor that
    takes an object of the same class as a parameter to copy its data.
    Private Constructor: A constructor with the private modifier, commonly used in the Singleton design pattern to restrict object instantiation to
    within the class itself. 


