4) What happens when we did not provide any constructor? How object is created?
-->When you do not provide any constructor in a Java class, the following happens:
    Compiler Generates a Default Constructor: The Java compiler automatically inserts a default constructor into your class during the compilation process.
    No-Argument Structure: This automatically generated constructor is a no-argument constructor, meaning it takes no parameters.
    Superclass Call: The first task of this default constructor is to call the no-argument constructor of its superclass (e.g., super()).
    If no explicit superclass is defined, it calls the constructor of java.lang.Object.
    Variable Initialization: It initializes all instance variables to their default values:
    Numeric types (int, double, etc.) are set to 0 or 0.0.
    Boolean types are set to false.
    Reference types (objects) are set to null. 

    How the Object is Created
    Object creation follows a specific sequence when the new keyword is used: 
    Memory Allocation: The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) allocates enough memory on the heap to hold all the instance variables for that object and its
    parent classes.
    Implicit Constructor Invocation: The JVM calls the compiler-generated default constructor.
    Super Constructor Chaining: The default constructor immediately calls its parent's constructor, a process that continues up the chain to java.lang.Object.
    Field Initialization: After the parent constructors have run, the JVM initializes instance variables to their default values (or any values assigned
    at the time of declaration).
    Reference Return: Once the initialization is complete, the new operator returns a reference (the memory address) of the newly created object to the variable. 
    
    Important Note: If you define any constructor manually (even a parameterized one), the compiler will not generate the default constructor.
    You must then explicitly provide a no-argument constructor if you wish to use one


5) What is the use of the this() keyword in a constructor?
-->In Java programming, the this() keyword is used within a constructor to invoke another constructor in the same class. This practice is commonly

    The primary uses and rules of the this() keyword in constructors include:
    Constructor Chaining: It allows you to call a specific constructor from another constructor within the same class, which helps in reusing initialization
    logic and reducing code duplication.
    Providing Default Values: It is often used in a default (no-argument) constructor to call a parameterized constructor with default values, 
    ensuring consistent object setup.
    First Statement Rule: A call to this() must be the very first statement in the constructor's body. If it is placed elsewhere, the code will fail to compile.
    Mutually Exclusive with super(): In any single constructor, you can use either this() or super(), but not both, because both are required to
    be the first statement.
    Avoiding Recursion: A constructor cannot call itself directly or indirectly in a way that creates a recursive loop, as this will lead to a compile-time error.


6) What is the use of the super() keyword in a constructor?
-->The super() keyword in a constructor is used to explicitly call the immediate parent class (superclass) constructor from a child class (subclass)
    constructor. It ensures that the parent part of the object is properly initialized before the child class initializes its own fields, promoting 
    code reusability. 
  
    Key Uses and Characteristics:
    Constructor Chaining: It ensures that base class properties are set up before subclass code executes.
    Parameterized Constructor Call: super(args) allows passing arguments to a parent constructor, which is essential if the parent class lacks a default,
    no-argument constructor.
    Mandatory First Statement: The call to super() must be the very first statement in the subclass constructor.
    Implicit Calling: If super() is not explicitly defined, Java automatically inserts a call to the parent's no-argument constructor (if it exists). 
    For example, in a Dog class extending Animal, super() inside the Dog constructor allows the Animal initialization logic to run first.


