8) Is it possible to override a constructor? What happens when we override a constructor?
-->No, it is not possible to override a constructor in Java. 
   
    Why Constructors Cannot Be Overridden
    In Java, overriding is a mechanism where a subclass provides its own specific implementation of a method inherited from a parent class. Constructors 
    do not meet the fundamental requirements for overriding because: 

    Constructors are not inherited: Unlike regular methods, constructors of a superclass are not inherited by its subclasses. Since they are not inherited,
    they cannot be overridden.
    Name mismatch: A constructor must always have the same name as the class it belongs to. In an inheritance relationship, the superclass and subclass have 
    different names, meaning their constructors inevitably have different names as well.
    No return type: Overriding requires a matching return type (or a covariant return type), but constructors do not have a return type.


9) What is constructor chaining?
-->Constructor chaining is a technique in object-oriented programming where one constructor calls another constructor, either within the same class 
    (using this()) or from a base class (using super()). It reduces code duplication by centralizing initialization logic and ensures that all inherited 
    fields are properly initialized. 


10) Can a constructor be private? If yes, why do we use it?
-->Yes, a constructor can be private. This means it can only be accessed from within the same class and cannot be used by other classes to create new objects. 

    We use private constructors for the following primary reasons:
    Singleton Pattern: To ensure that only one instance of a class ever exists. The class provides a single global access point (usually a static method
    like getInstance()) to that one instance.
    Utility Classes: To prevent the creation of objects for classes that only contain static methods or constants, such as the Java Math class. Since
    these methods are called directly on the class itself, an object is never needed.
    Factory Methods: To control how objects are created. Instead of using new, users must call a static factory method which might return a cached object, 
    /a specific subclass, or perform additional validation.
    Preventing Inheritance: To stop other classes from extending your class. A subclass must call a parent class constructor; if that constructor is private,
        the subclass cannot be instantiated, effectively making the class final.
    Constructor Chaining: To reuse code within the same class. You might have several public constructors that all call one central private constructor to do
        the heavy lifting.



11) Can an abstract class have a constructor?
-->Even though you cannot create objects of an abstract class directly, its constructor is used to:
    👉 Initialize common properties when a subclass object is created.
    🔹 How does it work?
    When you create an object of a subclass:
    Subclass constructor is called
    It automatically calls the abstract class constructor using super()
    Parent (abstract class) initialization happens first
    
    Yes, an abstract class can have a constructor. Although abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly using the new keyword, the constructor is
    executed when a concrete subclass is instantiated, allowing for the initialization of abstract class fields and common setup code shared across subclasses. 
 
    Key details about abstract class constructors:
    Purpose: They serve to initialize state/fields defined within the abstract class itself, preventing duplicate code in subclasses.
    Execution: When a child class constructor is called, it implicitly or explicitly calls super() to trigger the abstract class constructor.
    Default Constructor: If no constructor is defined, the compiler provides a default no-arg constructor.
    Access Modifiers: While they can be public, it is often best practice to use protected because abstract classes are intended for inheritance.
    No Abstract Constructors: Constructors themselves cannot be declared abstract because they cannot be overridden.



12) Can an interface have a constructor?
-->No, an interface in Java cannot have a constructor. 

    Why Interfaces Cannot Have Constructors
    The primary reasons for this restriction include:
    No Instantiation: Interfaces cannot be instantiated directly; you cannot create an object using the new keyword on an interface. Since constructors
    exist to initialize a newly created object, they are unnecessary for an interface.
    No Instance Variables: A constructor's job is to initialize non-static data members (instance variables). In an interface, all variables are implicitly
    public, static, and final (constants), meaning they must be initialized at the time of declaration.
    Contract vs. Implementation: Interfaces define a "contract" or a set of behaviors that a class must follow, whereas a constructor is part of a specific
    class's internal implementation.
    Multiple Inheritance: Java allows a class to implement multiple interfaces. If interfaces had constructors, it would create ambiguity and complexity 
    when trying to initialize multiple parent interface states during object creation. 


13) Can a constructor be static or abstract? Why or why not?
-->No, a constructor cannot be static or abstract in Java. Static belongs to the class (not instances), while constructors initialize new objects.
    Abstract implies an incomplete, overridable method, but constructors are not inherited and must have a concrete body to execute. 
       
        Why Constructors Cannot Be Static
        Instance Creation: Constructors are invoked via the new operator to initialize a specific instance. Static members are class-level and shared 
        across all instances.
        No Inheritance: Static members are inherited, but constructors are not.
        Alternative: Use static { ... } (static initialization blocks) for code that runs once when the class loads. 
        
        Why Constructors Cannot Be Abstract
        Mandatory Implementation: Abstract methods are incomplete and intended to be overridden in child classes. Constructors cannot be overridden
        (they cannot be inherited).
        Impl Geicit Execution: Constructors are called automatically by the JVM when an instance is created, requiring a defined body


14) Can a constructor be final?
-->No, a constructor cannot be declared as final in Java. 
    🔹 1. Can a constructor be static?
    👉 No
    🔍 Why?
    static members belong to the class, not to objects
    A constructor is used to create/initialize an object
    👉 If constructor were static:
    It would belong to the class
    But constructors are meant for object creation
    ➡️ ❌ This creates a contradiction
    
    🔹 2. Can a constructor be abstract?
    👉 No
    🔍 Why?
    abstract means no implementation (only declaration)
    Constructor must always have implementation
    👉 Also:
    Constructors are not inherited
    abstract methods must be overridden in subclasses
    ➡️ ❌ So constructor cannot be abstract

    No Overriding Required: The primary purpose of the final keyword for methods is to prevent them from being overridden by subclasses. However,
    constructors are never inherited in Java, which means they cannot be overridden by default.
    Redundancy: Since a constructor is already incapable of being overridden, adding the final modifier would be redundant and meaningless.
    Compiler Error: Attempting to use the final keyword in a constructor declaration will result in a compile-time error: modifier final not allowed here. 
    
    While the constructor itself cannot be final, you can achieve similar restrictions on object creation by: 
    Declaring the Class as final: This prevents the entire class from being subclassed.
    Using private Constructors: This prevents external classes from instantiating the class or extending it.


15) What is a copy constructor in Java?
-->A copy constructor in Java is a special constructor used to create a new object as an exact copy of an existing object of the same class. Instead of copying references, it copies the actual values of the fields, making it ideal for creating deep copies. It takes an instance of the same class as a parameter. 
       
        Key Aspects:
        Purpose: Duplicates an object's state without sharing references.
        How it works: It takes an existing object as a parameter, e.g., public MyClass(MyClass original) { ... }.
        Advantage: Unlike clone(), it doesn't require casting and handles final fields easily.
        Use Case: Ideal for creating independent copies to avoid unintended side effects when modifying data.

      class Student {
                int id;
                String name;
            
                // Parameterized constructor
                Student(int id, String name) {
                    this.id = id;
                    this.name = name;
                }
            
                // Copy constructor
                Student(Student s) {
                    this.id = s.id;
                    this.name = s.name;
                }
            
                void display() {
                    System.out.println(id + " " + name);
                }
            }
            
            public class Main {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                    Student s1 = new Student(101, "Karthikeya");
                    Student s2 = new Student(s1);  // copying object
            
                    s2.display();
                }
            }


16) What is the difference between a method and a constructor?
-->
| Feature                  | Constructor                                                | Method                                                  |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Purpose**              | Initializes the state of a newly created object            | Performs operations, calculations, or defines behavior  |
| **Name**                 | Must be exactly the same as the class name                 | Can be any valid name (usually camelCase)               |
| **Return Type**          | No return type (not even `void`)                           | Must have a return type (`int`, `String`, `void`, etc.) |
| **Invocation**           | Called automatically when an object is created using `new` | Must be called explicitly                               |
| **Inheritance**          | Not inherited                                              | Inherited (can be overridden)                           |
| **Default Availability** | Default constructor is provided if none is written         | No default method is provided                           |
| **Overloading**          | Can be overloaded                                          | Can be overloaded                                       |
| **Overriding**           | Cannot be overridden                                       | Can be overridden                                       |
| **Access Modifiers**     | Can be `public`, `private`, `protected`, or default        | Same (all access modifiers allowed)                     |
| **Execution Time**       | Executes only once at object creation                      | Can be executed multiple times                          |
| **Special Use**          | Used for object initialization                             | Used for business logic                                 |



17) Can we use final variables in constructors?
-->Yes, you can use the final keyword in relation to variables in a constructor, but there are two distinct ways this applies: 
    1. Initializing "Blank Final" Instance Variables
    You can declare a final instance variable without an initial value (known as a blank final variable) and then assign it a value inside the constructor. 
    Rule: If a final instance variable is not initialized during declaration, it must be initialized in every constructor of the class.
    Immutability: This is a common practice to create immutable objects where fields are set once during object creation and never changed again.
    Restriction: If you have already initialized a final variable at its declaration, you cannot re-assign it in the constructor. 
 
    2. Declaring Local Final Variables
    You can declare local variables as final inside the body of a constructor just as you would in any other method. 
    These local variables are only accessible within that specific constructor and cannot be reassigned once set. 

